<h1>DOG</h1>

<p>
The dog response emerges when stability is defined through attachment to routine, people, and familiar emotional patterns. The system does not prioritize abstract control or structure; it prioritizes continuity of what is known, even if that continuity is no longer present. Stability becomes tied to memory and relational familiarity rather than current reality.
</p>

<p>
Perception becomes anchored in recognition of what once existed. Changes in environment are filtered through comparison to past states, and unfamiliar conditions are often processed in relation to previous emotional anchors rather than independent evaluation.
</p>

<p>
Under stress, the system may attempt to restore lost familiarity by adapting itself to new conditions, even at personal cost. The drive is not to replace the past, but to reconnect to it through any available structure in the present environment.
</p>

<p>
In social environments, this manifests as strong attachment to people, routines, or emotional patterns that feel known. Separation or change is processed as instability, leading to attempts to re-establish continuity even when circumstances have shifted permanently.
</p>

<p>
In environmental contexts, stability is measured through repetition and predictability. The system prefers familiar structures and may adjust itself heavily to maintain proximity to known emotional anchors.
</p>

<p>
At its most extreme expression, this becomes self-adaptive loss of identity in order to preserve connection to what was familiar. The system may reshape itself entirely around restoring relational continuity.
</p>

<h3>Internal Presentation</h3>
<p>
Internally, this state operates through memory anchoring and continuity tracking. Emotional safety is derived from familiarity rather than independence.
</p>

<h3>External Presentation</h3>
<p>
Externally, this appears as strong attachment behaviors, routine reinforcement, and adaptation toward maintaining closeness to familiar people or patterns.
</p>

<h3>Influence Layer</h3>
<p>
Influence manifests as relational gravity. Environments tend to stabilize around emotional familiarity and repeated interaction structures.
</p>
